		"title"		: "Snappsy The Alligator (Did Not Ask to Be in This Book)",
		"text"		: "1\n00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:07,560\nWelcome to Storyline Online, brought to you by the SAG-AFTRA Foundation.\n\n2\n00:00:07,560 --> 00:00:16,120\nMy name is David Harbour, and today I will be reading \"Snappsy the Alligator (Did Not Ask to Be in This Book)\".\n\n3\n00:00:16,120 --> 00:00:19,320\nWords by Julie Falatko, pictures by Tim Miller.\n\n4\n00:00:20,180 --> 00:00:23,700\nSnappsy the alligator wasn't feeling like himself.\n\n5\n00:00:24,240 --> 00:00:28,380\nHis feet felt draggy. His skin felt baggy.\n\n6\n00:00:28,380 --> 00:00:31,060\nHis tail wouldn't swish this way and that.\n\n7\n00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:36,020\nAnd, worst of all, his big jaw wouldn't SNAP.\n\n8\n00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:38,560\n\"This is terrible!\n\n9\n00:00:39,340 --> 00:00:40,920\nI'm just hungry!\n\n10\n00:00:41,240 --> 00:00:45,700\nWhy is this rude narrator trying to make it seem like I need a nap?\"\n\n11\n00:00:46,140 --> 00:00:49,280\nSo Snappsy went off in search of food.\n\n12\n00:00:50,160 --> 00:00:53,300\nHe walked along the edge of the pond.\n\n13\n00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:57,280\nHe scooted up the tall, tall hill.\n\n14\n00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:02,800\nHe shimmied through the forest.\n\n15\n00:01:03,440 --> 00:01:09,300\n\"You're an awful narrator. You're just describing what you see in the illustrations.\"\n\n16\n00:01:09,860 --> 00:01:16,840\nSnappsy, the big, mean alligator, kept looking for food.\n\n17\n00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:24,020\nHe liked to eat tiny, defenseless birds and soft, fuzzy bunnies.\n\n18\n00:01:24,540 --> 00:01:30,760\nHe prowled through the forest, looking for victims, when he came to a—\n\n19\n00:01:31,300 --> 00:01:38,460\n\"It's just a store. A grocery store! It's where I buy my FOOD.\"\n\n20\n00:01:39,260 --> 00:01:43,860\nSnappsy looked hungrily at the other shoppers...\n\n21\n00:01:45,060 --> 00:01:50,160\n...while loading his cart with pudding, peanut butter, pita bread, and popcorn.\n\n22\n00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:55,720\nYes, Snappsy the alligator was particularly fond of a certain letter of the alphabet.\n\n23\n00:01:55,780 --> 00:01:59,180\n\"I don't only eat food that starts with the letter P.\n\n24\n00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:02,780\nYou don't have to make it seem like I only buy storybook food.\n\n25\n00:02:02,960 --> 00:02:08,780\nI'm also buying cheddar, apples, pretzels, pasta, pears—\"\n\n26\n00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:09,900\nAha!\n\n27\n00:02:10,420 --> 00:02:12,680\n\"It's just a coincidence!\"\n\n28\n00:02:13,420 --> 00:02:21,340\nSnappsy, the big, mean, hungry alligator, who only liked food that started with the letter P,\n\n29\n00:02:21,500 --> 00:02:25,380\ncarried his groceries back through the forest, back down the hill, back around the pond,\n\n30\n00:02:25,380 --> 00:02:30,560\nuntil he got to a surprisingly lopsided shack.\n\n31\n00:02:31,520 --> 00:02:34,180\n\"Oh, you are really cheesing me off.\n\n32\n00:02:35,540 --> 00:02:39,580\nIt's my house. I built it myself.\"\n\n33\n00:02:40,820 --> 00:02:41,900\nI'll say.\n\n34\n00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:49,540\nSnappsy the alligator took his groceries into his splinter-laden shed and slammed the door. Quite hard.\n\n35\n00:02:50,740 --> 00:02:51,700\nHe was inside.\n\n36\n00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:54,000\nStill inside.\n\n37\n00:02:55,060 --> 00:02:56,460\nWhat was he doing in there?\n\n38\n00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,780\nWas he making crafty plans?\n\n39\n00:02:59,300 --> 00:03:04,840\nWas he roasting innocent forest creatures that he already had stored in his freezer?\n\n40\n00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:09,360\nHad he fallen asleep?\n\n41\n00:03:10,860 --> 00:03:14,700\n\"I made a peanut butter sandwich and now I'm reading a book.\"\n\n42\n00:03:15,440 --> 00:03:20,420\nWell, you have to come out. The story is really boring now.\n\n43\n00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:24,840\n\"If you must know, I'm planning a party.\"\n\n44\n00:03:25,220 --> 00:03:32,380\nSnappsy the alligator, trying to better his reputation with the other animals, decided to throw a party.\n\n45\n00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,500\nSnappsy vacuumed the rug.\n\n46\n00:03:35,780 --> 00:03:38,520\nHe made goody bags for all his guests.\n\n47\n00:03:40,040 --> 00:03:43,840\nWait, those aren't goody bags. He's just taking out the garbage.\n\n48\n00:03:43,940 --> 00:03:49,860\nSnappsy should really put out goody bags for his guests. They love those.\n\n49\n00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:54,960\n\"You know what? I did not ask to be in this book!\n\n50\n00:03:55,100 --> 00:03:57,740\nI was just having a normal day!\n\n51\n00:03:57,740 --> 00:04:05,520\nAnd suddenly you were talking about what I was doing, so I'm throwing a party to make things more interesting!\n\n52\n00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:10,540\nI hope you're happy! Now I just want you to buzz off!\"\n\n53\n00:04:13,860 --> 00:04:14,860\n\"Thank you.\"\n\n54\n00:04:18,780 --> 00:04:22,460\n\"Oh, go ahead! I can hear you breathing!\"\n\n55\n00:04:23,980 --> 00:04:28,320\nSnappsy's party was shaping up to be quite a festive event.\n\n56\n00:04:28,740 --> 00:04:31,580\nColorful streamers hung from the ceiling.\n\n57\n00:04:31,580 --> 00:04:34,140\nThere were cubes of cheese and a bowl of punch.\n\n58\n00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:37,760\nSome kind of danceable music was playing.\n\n59\n00:04:37,940 --> 00:04:40,820\nThen Snappsy's friends started to arrive.\n\n60\n00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:47,540\nThey were laughing and dancing. They weren't hungry or thirsty.\n\n61\n00:04:47,800 --> 00:04:51,160\nThey looked like they were having a really good time.\n\n62\n00:04:51,160 --> 00:04:54,580\nYes, a fine time indeed...\n\n63\n00:04:54,820 --> 00:04:58,840\n\"Oh, all right! You can come in!\"\n\n64\n00:04:59,620 --> 00:05:00,920\nOh gosh. Me?!\n\n65\n00:05:01,580 --> 00:05:03,020\nThe humble narrator?\n\n66\n00:05:03,660 --> 00:05:04,940\nWell, I don't know.\n\n67\n00:05:05,660 --> 00:05:07,340\nLet me check my calendar.\n\n68\n00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,320\nI suppose I could come for an hour or two.\n\n69\n00:05:10,540 --> 00:05:14,300\nSomeone has to demonstrate proper dance steps.\n\n70\n00:05:14,760 --> 00:05:17,140\nAll the important guests had finally arrived.\n\n71\n00:05:17,140 --> 00:05:26,620\nAnd while Snappsy's sharp teeth were still glinting menacingly, he was actually a lovely host.\n\n72\n00:05:26,940 --> 00:05:29,020\n\"Does anyone want pudding?\"\n\n73\n00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:30,220\nAha!\n\n74\n00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:34,140\n\"Because pudding is really good.\"\n\n75\n00:05:34,860 --> 00:05:39,800\nAnd we all ate pudding and did the Chicken Dance.\n\n76\n00:05:40,660 --> 00:05:46,480\nWe were really looking forward to Snappsy throwing parties like this every week.\n\n77\n00:05:47,520 --> 00:05:49,120\nHey!\n\n78\n00:05:50,260 --> 00:05:51,540\nThe end.\n\n79\n00:05:51,840 --> 00:06:02,780\nI love reading. I think books are an amazing way to go inside of yourself and outside of yourself.\n\n80\n00:06:02,780 --> 00:06:08,740\nBecause you are able to get lost in another person's story, and another person's life,\n\n81\n00:06:08,740 --> 00:06:15,320\nand sometimes when we're feeling lots of things we can feel like we're all alone in these feelings,\n\n82\n00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:23,580\nand then you read a book and you realize that everybody has a lot of the same feelings and that you're not alone.\n\n83\n00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:27,500\nAnd that's a wonderful thing for a human being to feel.\n\n84\n00:06:27,500 --> 00:06:31,020\nLike you're part of something larger than just yourself.\n\n85\n00:06:31,020 --> 00:06:35,600\nAnd also, they're not like movies and TV because you get to cast them yourself\n\n86\n00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:37,880\nin your imagination and in your brain,\n\n87\n00:06:37,940 --> 00:06:42,180\nand you can choose whoever you want to play the parts in the book.\n\n88\n00:06:42,620 --> 00:06:44,520\nThank you for watching Storyline Online.\n\n89\n00:06:44,520 --> 00:06:46,340\nMake sure to check out all of our stories.\n\n90\n00:06:46,340 --> 00:06:48,460\nAnd keep watching and keep reading.",
